        ]
      },
      "metadata": {
        "federation_entity": {
          "contacts": ["ops@ta.example.com"],
          "federation_api_endpoint": "http://ta.example.com:9091/oidc/fedapi",
          "homepage_uri": "https://www.ta.example.com"
        }
      }
    }
</code></pre>



<p>This statement is information about the Trust Anchor, so both “iss” and “sub” are the Trust Anchor itself. The “metadata” is the one about this Trust Anchor and among those the most important claim here is “federation_api_endpoint”, which issues Subordinate Statement like the next section.</p>



<ol class="wp-block-list">
<li>Subordinate Statement Endpoint</li>
</ol>



<p>The HTTP GET request with the path /oidc/fedapi(*) looks like below:</p>



<p>(*)”federation_api_endpoint “ in Entity Configuration tells you which path you should use here.</p>



<pre class="wp-block-code"><code class="">GET /oidc/fedapi?sub=http%3A%2F%2Fia.example.com&amp;
iss=http%3A%2F%2Fta.example.com HTTP/1.1
Host: ta.example.com:9091

</code></pre>



<p>Query parameter “iss” is the one to specify who issues the requested Subordinate Statement. That is the Trust Anchor here, who also signs that statement. And Query parameter “sub” is the one to specify who is the subject of that statement. That is the Intermediate Authority here, who is authorized by the Issuer with that sign.</p>



<p>And the GET returns JWT, which payload is like below:</p>



<pre class="wp-block-code"><code class="">{
   "iss": "http://ta.example.com",
   "sub": "http://ia.example.com",
   "jwks": {
        "keys": [
          {
            "alg": "RS256",
            "e": "AQAB",
            "kty": "RSA",
            "use": "sig",
            "kid": "78e94429-8454-4088-8f60-0210de4278d9",
